    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>End the Electoral College</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lawrence R Foster letter holds amendment to United States Constitution should replace 'archaic' electoral vote system with direct vote (Sept 25 Op-Ed by Michael Yaki)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Election? What Election?'', by Michael Yaki (Op-Ed, Sept. 25): The problem of being ignored in presidential elections is not limited to California and New York. In most elections, more than half the states are ignored. Voters who don't live in so-called swing states are in effect bystanders in these quadrennial events.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Election? What Election?'', by Michael Yaki (Op-Ed, Sept. 25): The problem of being ignored in presidential elections is not limited to California and New York. In most elections, more than half the states are ignored. Voters who don't live in so-called swing states are in effect bystanders in these quadrennial events.</p>
        <p>There is a solution to this troublesome problem that would also eliminate the possibility that a candidate could enter the White House with an electoral vote majority while losing the popular vote, as has happened twice. An amendment to the United States Constitution should replace the archaic electoral vote system with a direct vote. Only in this manner will citizens in all 50 states be able to take part fully in selecting our nation's leaders.</p>
        <p>LAWRENCE R. FOSTER  San Ramon, Calif., Sept. 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
